templates:
  generic:
    description: Generic configuration guide for features not covered by specialized
      sub-templates
    variables_required:
    - feature_name
    - odoo_version
    template: 'Configuring {feature_name} in Odoo {odoo_version} requires understanding
      the relationship between company-level settings, user permissions, and transactional
      workflows before clicking Save on configuration screens that affect every user''s
      daily operations. Incorrect {feature_name} configuration forces workarounds
      that compound into permanent operational inefficiencies—users develop habits
      around system limitations that persist even after you fix the underlying configuration.


      The configuration process follows a hierarchical structure where high-level
      settings constrain subsequent options. Company-level configurations establish
      boundaries for all users and transactions. User group permissions determine
      which employees access which features. Transaction-level settings customize
      behavior for specific document types. Configuring in the wrong order creates
      contradictions that generate cryptic error messages and unexpected behavior.


      ## Configuration Prerequisites and Dependencies


      {feature_name} depends on several prerequisite modules and configurations. {prerequisite_modules}


      Verify these dependencies exist before attempting {feature_name} configuration.
      Missing prerequisites cause configuration screens to display incomplete options
      or error messages about undefined fields. The error messages don''t explicitly
      state which prerequisite is missing—you must deduce this from Odoo''s dependency
      chain.


      ## Company-Level Configuration


      Navigate to Settings > Companies and select your company record. The {feature_name}
      configuration section appears under {settings_location}. {company_config_specifics}


      Company-level settings apply globally to all users and transactions unless explicitly
      overridden by user group permissions or transaction-specific configurations.
      Think carefully before enabling company-wide settings—disabling them later requires
      data migration to handle records created while the setting was active.


      {feature_specific_company_settings}


      Test company-level changes in a development environment first. Some settings
      trigger database migrations that take minutes or hours to complete based on
      transaction volume. Running these migrations in production during business hours
      creates unexpected downtime.


      ## User Permissions and Access Rights


      {feature_name} functionality requires specific user group assignments. Navigate
      to Settings > Users & Companies > Groups and review the {relevant_groups} groups.
      {permission_specifics}


      The permission model follows a hierarchical structure where higher-level groups
      include all permissions from lower-level groups. Granting "Manager" access automatically
      includes "User" permissions—you don''t need to assign both. However, custom
      permission configurations can break this hierarchy if you modify out-of-box
      group definitions.


      Test permissions with actual user accounts, not the administrator account. Administrators
      bypass many permission checks, creating false confidence that configuration
      works when normal users will encounter access denied errors. Create test accounts
      for each user role and verify they can perform required operations.


      ## Feature-Specific Configuration


      {feature_name} provides numerous configuration options that customize behavior
      for your business processes. {feature_detailed_config}


      Document every configuration change with business justification and expected
      impact. Configuration screens don''t provide change history or rollback capability—if
      a setting change causes problems, you must remember the previous value to restore
      it. Maintain a configuration change log in a shared document accessible to the
      entire implementation team.


      ## Integration with Other Modules


      {feature_name} integrates with other Odoo modules that may require additional
      configuration. {integration_requirements}


      Test integrations explicitly—don''t assume they work because individual modules
      function correctly. Create test scenarios that span multiple modules: create
      a sales order that triggers inventory picking that updates accounting entries.
      Verify the complete workflow before declaring configuration complete.


      ## Workflow Configuration


      {feature_name} workflows define how records progress through business process
      stages. {workflow_specifics}


      Workflow stages should reflect your actual business process, not Odoo''s default
      assumptions. If your sales process requires manager approval for discounts exceeding
      10%, configure approval workflows rather than training users to manually notify
      managers. Automated workflow enforcement prevents process bypassing that occurs
      when workflows exist only in employee training materials.


      ## Validation Rules and Constraints


      Configure validation rules to prevent data entry errors at transaction creation
      time rather than discovering problems during reports. {validation_config_specifics}


      Validation rules should be strict enough to prevent obvious errors but flexible
      enough to handle legitimate edge cases. Rules that are too restrictive force
      users to enter dummy data to bypass validation, defeating the purpose. Test
      validation rules with real historical data to identify edge cases that require
      rule adjustments.


      ## Reporting and Analytics Configuration


      Configure {feature_name} reports to match your business reporting requirements.
      {reporting_config_details}


      Custom report configurations should match your existing reporting templates
      to minimize disruption for stakeholders consuming reports. If your CFO expects
      gross profit calculations to exclude shipping revenue, configure reports identically—don''t
      force stakeholders to adapt to Odoo''s calculation methods.


      ## Testing Configuration Changes


      Create a comprehensive test plan covering all {feature_name} workflows. {testing_specifics}


      Test with real production data volumes, not 5-10 sample records. Configuration
      that works with sample data often fails at scale due to query timeout issues,
      memory exhaustion, or UI slowdowns when dropdown lists contain thousands of
      options.


      ## Common Configuration Mistakes


      **Configuring permissions too restrictively**: Users cannot perform legitimate
      operations and submit support tickets for every exception. This creates administrative
      burden and user frustration. Start with permissive settings and tighten based
      on actual security requirements, not theoretical worst-case scenarios.


      **Ignoring performance implications**: Configuration options that seem innocuous
      in testing devastate performance in production. Enabling audit trails on high-volume
      transaction tables generates gigabytes of log data daily and slows queries by
      40-60%.


      **Not documenting custom configurations**: Six months after go-live, users ask
      why a feature behaves differently than documented in Odoo''s official guides.
      Without configuration documentation, diagnosing customizations versus bugs wastes
      hours of troubleshooting time.


      **Changing production configuration without testing**: "This is a small change,
      we don''t need to test it" becomes the cause of the next production outage.
      Always test configuration changes in staging environments, even apparently trivial
      ones. Edge cases and integration impacts aren''t obvious without testing.

      '
