  manufacturing:
    description: 'Manufacturing configuration including BOM types, routing, capacity
      planning, job costing, and by-products [Refactored: 7 TOP features + defaults]
      [Refactored: 7 TOP features + defaults] [Refactored: 7 TOP features + defaults]
      [Refactored: 7 TOP features + defaults]'
    variables_required:
    - feature_name
    - odoo_version
    - manufacturing_category
    template: 'Configuring {feature_name} in Odoo {odoo_version} requires understanding
      how production orders execute, how materials flow through work centers, and
      how costing calculations aggregate before committing BOM structures that affect
      every manufactured product in your catalog. Incorrect {feature_name} configuration
      creates material shortages, inaccurate production costs, and shop floor confusion
      that compounds across hundreds of manufacturing orders—planners develop manual
      workarounds that persist even after you fix the underlying configuration.


      Manufacturing configuration in Odoo differs fundamentally from other modules
      because changes to BOM structures, routing operations, or costing methods retroactively
      affect existing production orders and work-in-progress inventory valuations.
      A seemingly minor change to a phantom BOM can cascade through your entire product
      hierarchy, changing material requirements for finished goods three levels up
      in your product structure.


      {feature_specific_intro}


      ## {feature_name} Configuration Workflow


      {feature_setup_workflow}


      ### Prerequisites and Module Dependencies


      {feature_name} requires the Manufacturing (MRP) module and related dependencies
      installed before accessing configuration screens:


      {prerequisite_configuration}


      Navigate to Apps, search for "Manufacturing" and "Inventory", click Install.
      Odoo automatically configures basic manufacturing workflows, but {feature_name}
      requires additional setup beyond default installation.


      ## Core BOM and Production Settings


      {core_settings_section}


      ### BOM Structure and Computation Logic


      {bom_computation_logic}


      BOM consumption calculations execute at production order confirmation, not at
      order creation. Changes to BOM components after production order creation don''t
      affect already-confirmed orders. Test BOM structure changes in development environment
      with representative product hierarchies before deploying to production.


      ### Work Center and Routing Configuration


      {routing_configuration}


      Work center capacity constraints apply at work order scheduling, preventing
      overallocation when multiple production orders compete for limited resources.
      Configure realistic capacity limits based on actual equipment throughput, not
      theoretical maximum capacity.


      ## Production Planning and Scheduling


      {production_planning}


      ### Automation and MRP Triggers


      {automation_configuration}


      Automated procurement follows MRP logic: reordering rules trigger based on forecasted
      demand minus on-hand inventory minus in-transit purchases plus reserved quantities.
      Misconfigured rules create either excess inventory or stockouts, both expensive
      outcomes.


      ## Advanced Manufacturing Options


      {advanced_options}


      ### Integration with Inventory and Purchasing


      {integration_points}


      Manufacturing orders automatically create inventory moves when confirmed, reserve
      components when scheduled, and consume materials when work orders complete.
      Inventory valuation methods (FIFO, AVCO) affect production cost calculations—changing
      valuation methods mid-year creates accounting nightmares.


      ## Costing and Valuation Configuration


      {costing_configuration}


      Product costing in manufacturing aggregates component costs, work center labor/overhead
      rates, and by-product/scrap valuations. Real-time costing updates as production
      progresses, but many companies prefer standard costing with periodic variance
      analysis to avoid constant inventory revaluations.


      ## User Access and Permission Configuration


      {feature_name} permissions follow Odoo''s role-based access control model. Navigate
      to Settings > Users & Companies > Groups to configure manufacturing access levels:


      {permission_matrix}


      Manufacturing permissions cascade through production order lifecycle: users
      who can create production orders cannot necessarily confirm them, users who
      can confirm orders cannot necessarily mark work orders done. Design permission
      structure matching your shop floor approval workflow.


      ## Performance Optimization and Best Practices


      {performance_optimization}


      ### Reporting and Analytics Configuration


      Configure {feature_name} reporting to track production efficiency, material
      consumption variance, and manufacturing cost accuracy:


      {reporting_configuration}


      Production reports should mirror shop floor tracking systems. If your manufacturing
      manager tracks efficiency by work center utilization, configure Odoo reports
      identically rather than forcing stakeholders to learn new KPI definitions.


      ## Common Configuration Mistakes and Solutions


      {common_mistakes}


      ### Testing and Validation Checklist


      Before declaring {feature_name} configuration complete, validate these manufacturing
      scenarios with production-scale complexity:


      {validation_checklist}


      Configuration that works for simple products (5 components, 2 operations) often
      breaks with complex assemblies (50+ components, 10+ operations, nested sub-assemblies)
      due to BOM explosion timeouts, routing calculation errors, or capacity scheduling
      failures.

      '
    variable_mappings:
      feature_specific_intro:
        Manufacturing Bom: 'Bill of Materials (BOM) configuration defines the recipe
          for transforming raw materials into finished products, specifying exact
          component quantities, consumption timing, and production sequencing. Incorrect
          BOM configuration causes material shortages mid-production when components
          aren''t available as expected, cost calculation errors that misstate product
          profitability, and shop floor confusion when assembly instructions don''t
          match actual component requirements.

          '
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: 'Routing configuration establishes the sequence
          of operations transforming components into finished products, defining work
          centers, operation durations, and resource requirements. Misconfigured routing
          creates unrealistic production schedules when operation times don''t reflect
          actual manufacturing capacity, work center bottlenecks when routing bypasses
          critical quality control steps, and inaccurate cost calculations when labor/overhead
          allocation doesn''t match actual production patterns.

          '
        Manufacturing Phantom Bom: 'Phantom BOM configuration defines intermediate
          assemblies that exist conceptually in product structure but never physically
          stock in inventory, enabling simplified production planning while maintaining
          detailed component tracking. Incorrect phantom BOM setup causes material
          requirement explosion errors when planning systems don''t properly cascade
          through phantom levels, inventory discrepancies when system expects phantom
          assemblies in stock, and production confusion when shop floor instructions
          reference non-existent intermediate products.

          '
        Manufacturing Flexible Bom: 'Flexible BOM configuration enables variant production
          where component substitutions adapt to material availability, customer specifications,
          or cost optimization without maintaining separate BOMs for every product
          variation. Incorrect flexible BOM setup causes production errors when invalid
          component substitutions create quality issues, cost variance when substitution
          logic doesn''t account for price differences, and inventory imbalances when
          substitute components aren''t properly reserved for production orders.

          '
        Manufacturing Capacity Planning: 'Capacity planning configuration establishes
          production constraints based on work center availability, labor resources,
          and equipment limitations, preventing over-scheduling and enabling realistic
          delivery commitments. Misconfigured capacity planning creates impossible
          production schedules when system ignores actual equipment throughput, shop
          floor chaos when multiple production orders compete for constrained resources,
          and missed customer delivery dates when scheduling algorithms don''t account
          for maintenance downtime or shift patterns.

          '
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: 'Master Production Schedule (MPS)
          configuration defines demand forecasts that drive material procurement and
          production planning, balancing customer orders against inventory targets
          and capacity constraints. Incorrect MPS configuration causes either excess
          inventory when forecasts exceed actual demand or stockouts when planning
          doesn''t anticipate demand spikes, procurement chaos when material requirements
          change daily as MPS fluctuates, and production inefficiency when shop floor
          constantly adjusts schedules chasing MPS changes.

          '
        Manufacturing Job Costing: 'Job costing configuration tracks actual production
          costs against estimated costs at individual manufacturing order level, enabling
          profitability analysis and cost variance identification. Misconfigured job
          costing creates inaccurate cost reporting when labor/overhead allocation
          methods don''t reflect actual resource consumption, profitability illusions
          when by-product credits aren''t properly applied, and variance analysis
          confusion when standard costs don''t periodically update to reflect current
          material prices.

          '
        default: This configuration feature plays a critical role in Odoo's operational
          functionality. Proper configuration ensures seamless integration with your
          business processes and delivers expected outcomes. Misconfiguration creates
          operational friction that compounds into permanent inefficiencies, forcing
          users to develop workarounds that persist even after the underlying issue
          is fixed. Configuration decisions made here affect all users and transactions
          across the system.
      feature_setup_workflow:
        Manufacturing Bom: "1. Navigate to Manufacturing > Configuration > Bill of\
          \ Materials\n2. Click Create and select the product to manufacture\n3. Define\
          \ BOM Type (Manufacture this product, Kit, or Subcontracting)\n4. Add component\
          \ lines specifying:\n   - Component product and quantity\n   - Consumption\
          \ timing (when used or when order confirmed)\n   - Apply on variants (if\
          \ product has variants)\n5. Set BOM reference and revision tracking\n6.\
          \ Configure flexible consumption (allow component substitutions)\n7. Define\
          \ BoM routing operations (if using work centers)\n8. Test BOM explosion\
          \ by creating sample manufacturing order\n"
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: "1. Navigate to Manufacturing > Configuration\
          \ > Settings\n2. Enable \"Work Orders\" feature under Manufacturing Order\n\
          3. Go to Manufacturing > Configuration > Operations\n4. Create work centers\
          \ defining:\n   - Work center name and code\n   - Working time calendar\
          \ (shift schedules)\n   - Time efficiency and capacity\n   - Cost per hour\
          \ for labor and overhead\n5. Create routing operations specifying:\n   -\
          \ Operation name and work center\n   - Default duration (setup + per-unit\
          \ time)\n   - Worksheet instructions (text or PDF)\n6. Link routing to BOM\
          \ (one routing per BOM)\n7. Configure quality control points at specific\
          \ operations\n"
        Manufacturing Phantom Bom: '1. Navigate to Manufacturing > Configuration >
          Bill of Materials

          2. Create BOM for intermediate assembly product

          3. Set BOM Type to "Kit" (phantom behavior)

          4. Enable "Apply Immediate Consumption" for true phantom behavior

          5. Add all sub-components with exact quantities

          6. Create parent-level BOM referencing phantom assembly

          7. Test material explosion ensuring system bypasses phantom level

          8. Verify manufacturing order doesn''t create work orders for phantom assembly

          '
        Manufacturing Flexible Bom: "1. Navigate to Manufacturing > Configuration\
          \ > Settings\n2. Enable \"Product Variants\" and \"Flexible BoM\" features\n\
          3. Create product template with variant attributes\n4. Go to Bill of Materials,\
          \ create flexible BOM\n5. Add components with \"Apply on Variants\" conditions:\n\
          \   - Specific variant attributes (e.g., Color=Red requires red paint)\n\
          \   - Variant-specific quantities\n6. Define default components (apply to\
          \ all variants)\n7. Set component substitution priorities\n8. Test with\
          \ multiple variant combinations ensuring correct components selected\n"
        Manufacturing Capacity Planning: "1. Navigate to Manufacturing > Configuration\
          \ > Work Centers\n2. For each work center, configure:\n   - Working time\
          \ calendar (shifts, holidays, breaks)\n   - Time efficiency percentage (actual\
          \ vs. theoretical)\n   - Capacity (parallel operations or pieces per hour)\n\
          \   - OEE factors (availability, performance, quality)\n3. Go to Planning\
          \ > Configuration > Settings\n4. Enable \"Finite Capacity Planning\" feature\n\
          5. Configure planning horizon and scheduling rules\n6. Set capacity constraint\
          \ handling (reschedule or alert)\n7. Test scheduling with overlapping production\
          \ orders\n"
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: "1. Navigate to Manufacturing >\
          \ Configuration > Settings\n2. Enable \"Master Production Schedule\" feature\n\
          3. Go to Manufacturing > Planning > Master Production Schedule\n4. Create\
          \ MPS entries for each planned product:\n   - Product and forecast quantity\n\
          \   - Planning period (weekly or monthly buckets)\n   - Safety stock target\n\
          5. Configure demand sources (sales orders, forecasts, min/max rules)\n6.\
          \ Set replenishment frequency and lead time\n7. Run MRP to generate procurement\
          \ proposals\n8. Review proposed manufacturing orders and purchase orders\n"
        Manufacturing Job Costing: "1. Navigate to Manufacturing > Configuration >\
          \ Settings\n2. Enable \"Work Orders\" and \"By-Products\" features\n3. Go\
          \ to Inventory > Configuration > Settings\n4. Set inventory valuation to\
          \ \"Automated\" (perpetual) with \"Real Price\" costing\n5. For each work\
          \ center, configure hourly costs:\n   - Labor cost per hour\n   - Overhead/burden\
          \ rate\n6. Create manufacturing order and track actual consumption\n7. Compare\
          \ actual costs against standard costs in Manufacturing Analysis\n8. Configure\
          \ cost variance alerts for exceeding thresholds\n"
        default: '1. **Access Configuration**: Navigate to the appropriate Configuration
          menu within the relevant module

          2. **Review Prerequisites**: Verify required modules are installed and company
          settings configured

          3. **Configure Core Settings**: Define key parameters and default values

          4. **Set User Permissions**: Assign appropriate access rights to user groups

          5. **Test Configuration**: Create test records to verify behavior matches
          requirements

          6. **Document Changes**: Record configuration decisions and expected impacts

          7. **Deploy to Production**: Apply validated settings to live environment'
      prerequisite_configuration:
        Manufacturing Bom: Install Manufacturing (MRP) and Inventory modules. Configure
          product categories with 'Can be Manufactured' enabled. Create all component
          products with accurate lead times and suppliers.
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Install Manufacturing module with Work Orders
          feature enabled. Create work centers representing actual production equipment.
          Configure work center calendars matching shop floor shift schedules.
        Manufacturing Phantom Bom: Install Manufacturing and Inventory modules. Enable
          multi-level BOM processing in Manufacturing settings. Create intermediate
          assembly products with 'Phantom' procurement route.
        Manufacturing Flexible Bom: Install Manufacturing module with Product Variants
          feature enabled. Create product template with attribute values (color, size,
          etc.). Configure variant-specific procurement rules.
        Manufacturing Capacity Planning: Install Manufacturing and Planning modules.
          Enable Work Orders and MPS features. Configure company working time calendar
          defining business days and hours.
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: Install Manufacturing module with
          MPS feature enabled. Configure reordering rules on products. Enable automated
          procurement in Inventory settings.
        Manufacturing Job Costing: Install Manufacturing and Accounting modules. Configure
          perpetual inventory valuation with real-time costing. Set up work center
          hourly rates for all production resources.
        default: '- **Required modules**: Core Odoo modules must be installed before
          configuring this feature

          - **User permissions**: Appropriate access rights for configuration and
          usage

          - **Company settings**: Basic company configuration completed including
          fiscal year and currency

          - **Database backup**: Recent backup before making configuration changes

          - **Test environment**: Development instance available for testing before
          production deployment'
      core_settings_section:
        Manufacturing Bom: Access Manufacturing > Configuration > Settings. Enable
          'Multi-Level BoM' to support nested assemblies. Configure BoM versioning
          if tracking engineering changes. Set default consumption method (strict
          or flexible) for component usage. Enable 'BoM Cost' to display manufacturing
          cost breakdowns.
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Navigate to Manufacturing > Configuration
          > Work Centers. For each work center, configure capacity (pieces/hour or
          concurrent operations), costs (labor + overhead rates), and working time
          calendars. Set time efficiency factor (typically 85-95% of theoretical maximum).
        Manufacturing Phantom Bom: In BOM configuration, select 'Kit' as BoM Type
          for phantom behavior. Enable 'Phantom' on intermediate product's Inventory
          tab. System treats phantom as pass-through during material requirement planning,
          bypassing intermediate product creation.
        Manufacturing Flexible Bom: Create product variants via Attributes & Values
          under product template. In BoM lines, use 'Apply on Variants' field to conditionally
          include components based on variant attributes. System dynamically generates
          BoM for specific variant at production order creation.
        Manufacturing Capacity Planning: Configure work center capacity as either
          'Pieces per hour' (for discrete manufacturing) or 'Concurrent Operations'
          (for continuous/batch). Set realistic time efficiency accounting for changeovers,
          breaks, unplanned downtime. Enable 'Finite Capacity' to prevent overloading.
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: Define forecast buckets (weekly/monthly)
          matching sales planning cycle. Set safety stock targets based on demand
          variability and lead time. Configure procurement method (make-to-stock vs.
          make-to-order) affecting when manufacturing orders generate.
        Manufacturing Job Costing: 'Enable real-time costing in Inventory > Configuration
          > Settings. For each work center, set hourly labor and overhead rates. Choose
          costing method: average cost (simple, smooths fluctuations) or real price
          (accurate, volatile based on actual costs).'
        default: Configuration options are accessible through the module's Configuration
          menu. Key settings include enabling/disabling feature flags, defining default
          values, establishing validation rules, and customizing behavior to match
          your business requirements. Configuration changes typically apply at company
          level unless explicitly scoped to user groups or specific records. Review
          each setting carefully as changes affect system-wide behavior.
      bom_computation_logic:
        Manufacturing Bom: 'BoM consumption calculates material requirements recursively
          through nested assemblies. Top-level BoM explodes to show all leaf-level
          components with multiplied quantities. Component consumption timing controls
          reservation: ''When order confirmed'' reserves immediately, ''When component
          used'' reserves at work order start.'
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Routing operations execute sequentially
          unless marked as parallel. Total manufacturing lead time sums setup times,
          per-unit operation times × quantity, and inter-operation transfer times.
          Work center capacity constraints may extend lead time beyond routing duration
          when work center overloaded.
        Manufacturing Phantom Bom: Phantom BoM explosion bypasses intermediate assembly
          level during MRP calculation. System directly reserves leaf components without
          creating intermediate product inventory moves. Phantom assemblies appear
          on production documentation for shop floor guidance but don't generate separate
          manufacturing orders.
        Manufacturing Flexible Bom: Flexible BoM evaluates variant conditions at manufacturing
          order creation, generating variant-specific component list. System checks
          'Apply on Variants' conditions matching order's product variant. Components
          without variant restrictions apply to all variants (common components).
        Manufacturing Capacity Planning: 'Capacity planning calculates available time
          per work center: working hours × time efficiency × (1 - downtime percentage).
          Scheduled load accumulates operation durations from all manufacturing orders.
          When scheduled load exceeds available capacity, planning either reschedules
          to future periods or raises capacity alert.'
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: 'MPS runs MRP calculation generating
          procurement proposals: manufacturing orders for make items, purchase orders
          for buy items. Calculation considers demand (sales orders + forecast), supply
          (on-hand + in-transit + planned), and parameters (safety stock, lead time).
          MRP re-plans daily or on-demand.'
        Manufacturing Job Costing: Job costing aggregates component costs (average
          or real), work center labor costs (hours × hourly rate), overhead costs
          (hours × overhead rate), and additional costs (subcontracting, external
          services). Real-time valuation updates product cost as manufacturing order
          progresses.
        default: Bill of Materials calculations determine component quantities, cost
          rollup, and production feasibility. Configure BOM computation rules to match
          your manufacturing processes and inventory management practices.
      routing_configuration:
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Create routing defining operation sequence.
          Each operation specifies work center, default duration (setup time + per-unit
          run time), and worksheet (instructions). Operations can run sequentially
          (one after another) or parallel (simultaneously). Link routing to BoM—one
          routing per BoM. Work orders generate for each routing operation when manufacturing
          order confirmed.
        Manufacturing Bom: If routing enabled, specify at which operation each component
          consumed. Early consumption (Operation 1) reserves components at production
          start. Late consumption (Operation 5) allows flexibility if earlier operations
          yield rejects. Backflush consumption (When order done) consumes components
          automatically at completion without manual confirmation.
        Manufacturing Capacity Planning: Routing duration calculations feed capacity
          planning. Finite capacity planning checks work center availability before
          scheduling operations. If work center overloaded, scheduler either delays
          operation start (pushing delivery date) or raises capacity warning requiring
          manual intervention.
        Manufacturing Job Costing: Routing operations link to work centers defining
          labor and overhead rates. Actual work order duration × work center hourly
          rate calculates operation cost. Compare actual operation duration against
          routing standard to identify efficiency variances. Excessive overtime or
          low yields create cost overruns.
        default: Work center routing defines production sequences, timing estimates,
          and resource allocation. Configure routing paths to optimize production
          flow and provide accurate capacity planning.
      production_planning:
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: MPS dashboard shows forecasted demand,
          actual orders, projected inventory, and procurement proposals per period.
          Green indicators show sufficient inventory, yellow shows approaching minimum
          stock, red shows stockout risk. Approve procurement proposals converting
          to confirmed manufacturing/purchase orders. Re-run MPS after demand changes
          to update proposals.
        Manufacturing Capacity Planning: Capacity planning view displays work center
          load chart showing scheduled hours vs. available hours per period. Overloaded
          periods display red, underutilized periods display green. Drag operations
          between periods to manually reschedule. Configure automatic leveling rules
          to balance load across available capacity.
        Manufacturing Bom: 'Plan manufacturing orders from MPS, sales orders, or manual
          creation. Manufacturing order confirms BoM at order creation—subsequent
          BoM changes don''t affect existing orders. Schedule production considering
          component lead times: manufacturing order start date must allow sufficient
          time for component procurement before production begins.'
        default: Production scheduling integrates demand forecasts, available capacity,
          and material availability. Configure planning parameters to balance production
          efficiency with inventory costs and customer delivery requirements.
      automation_configuration:
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: Configure automated MRP scheduling
          (daily cron job or on-demand trigger). Set procurement proposal auto-approval
          for trusted products. Enable automatic manufacturing order confirmation
          when all components available. Configure exception alerts for stockouts,
          capacity overloads, or late deliveries.
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Configure work order auto-start when prior
          operation completes. Enable automatic component backflushing at operation
          completion (reduces data entry but risks accuracy). Set automated quality
          checks at critical operations triggering inspection workflow before proceeding.
        Manufacturing Capacity Planning: Enable automatic rescheduling when capacity
          exceeded—system pushes operations to future periods maintaining delivery
          commitments. Configure alert emails when specific work centers approach
          capacity limits. Set automatic overtime calculations when demand requires
          extended hours.
        default: Automation is supported through scheduled actions, automated actions,
          and server actions. Configure automation triggers based on record creation,
          field changes, or time-based schedules. Automated processes reduce manual
          data entry, enforce business rules consistently, and ensure timely execution
          of recurring tasks.
      advanced_options:
        Manufacturing Bom: Configure BoM versioning for engineering change management.
          Enable BoM comparison showing differences between versions. Set effectivity
          dates controlling when BoM becomes active. Configure BoM approval workflows
          requiring engineering and procurement signoff before activation.
        Manufacturing Flexible Bom: Advanced flexible BoM supports conditional logic
          beyond simple variant matching. Configure component substitution hierarchies
          (preferred → acceptable → emergency alternatives). Enable make/buy decisions
          dynamically based on component availability or cost thresholds.
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Configure parallel operations executing
          simultaneously on different work centers. Enable operation splitting processing
          large batches across multiple machines. Set operation overlap allowing next
          operation to start before prior operation completes (useful for continuous
          flow production).
        Manufacturing Job Costing: Enable variance analysis comparing actual costs
          against standard costs. Configure variance thresholds triggering management
          alerts (e.g., >10% cost overrun). Set up cost rollup for multi-level assemblies
          showing cost contribution by component and operation.
        default: Advanced configuration options provide fine-grained control over
          this feature behavior. These settings handle edge cases, enable optional
          features, and customize system responses to specific scenarios. Review advanced
          options carefully as they may introduce complexity that increases maintenance
          overhead.
      integration_points:
        Manufacturing Bom: BoM integrates with Inventory (component availability),
          Purchasing (procurement proposals), Sales (configure-to-order), and Accounting
          (cost valuation). Manufacturing order confirmation creates inventory reservations.
          Component availability issues block order confirmation until components
          procured.
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Routing integrates with Quality (inspection
          points), Maintenance (preventive maintenance scheduling), Timesheets (labor
          tracking), and Planning (capacity scheduling). Work order completion triggers
          quality checks before allowing next operation or finished product receipt.
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: MPS integrates with Sales (customer
          orders), Forecasting (demand planning), Inventory (stock levels), and Purchasing
          (vendor lead times). MRP calculation considers all demand sources generating
          unified procurement plan. Changes to sales forecasts trigger MPS replanning.
        Manufacturing Job Costing: Job costing integrates with Accounting (general
          ledger posting), Inventory (valuation updates), Payroll (labor cost capture),
          and Sales (profitability analysis). Manufacturing order completion posts
          work-in-progress to finished goods inventory at calculated cost.
        default: Integration with multiple Odoo modules including sales, purchasing,
          inventory, and accounting. Configuration determines which integration points
          are active, how data synchronizes across modules, and what validation rules
          apply to integrated records.
      costing_configuration:
        Manufacturing Job Costing: 'Select costing method per product category: Standard
          costing (fixed cost updated periodically) provides stable pricing but requires
          variance analysis. Average costing (moving average of actual costs) reflects
          current costs but creates price volatility. FIFO costing (first-in-first-out)
          matches costs to specific batches but adds complexity.'
        Manufacturing Bom: Component costing flows up through BoM hierarchy. Leaf
          components use purchase cost or prior manufacturing cost. Each assembly
          level adds component costs plus operation costs. Verify cost rollup calculations
          periodically as component prices and labor rates change.
        default: Cost calculation methods determine how expenses are tracked and allocated.
          Configure costing approaches to match accounting requirements and provide
          accurate financial reporting.
      permission_matrix:
        Manufacturing Bom: Manufacturing / User can view BOMs and create manufacturing
          orders. Manufacturing / Manager can create/edit BOMs and approve engineering
          changes. Restrict BoM editing to engineering team preventing unauthorized
          modifications. Enable BOM revision tracking showing who changed what when.
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Manufacturing / User can view work orders
          and record production. Manufacturing / Manager can create/modify routing
          operations and work centers. Shop floor supervisors need work order completion
          permission without routing modification access.
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: Manufacturing / Planner can run
          MRP and create procurement proposals. Manufacturing / Manager can approve
          proposals and adjust planning parameters. Restrict MPS modification to demand
          planners preventing unauthorized forecast changes.
        Manufacturing Job Costing: Manufacturing / User can view production costs.
          Manufacturing / Manager can modify work center rates and costing methods.
          Accounting / Manager can adjust cost variance accounts and valuation methods.
          Separate duties between operations (production tracking) and accounting
          (cost configuration).
        default: 'User access is controlled through Odoo''s role-based permission
          system. Configure user groups to grant appropriate access levels: view-only
          access for data consumers, creation/edit rights for operational users, and
          full configuration access for system administrators. Test permissions with
          non-administrative accounts to verify security model works correctly.'
      performance_optimization:
        Manufacturing Bom: Index product variants for fast BOM lookup. Cache BOM explosion
          calculations for frequently-produced products. Limit BOM nesting depth to
          7 levels maximum preventing explosion timeout. Archive obsolete BOMs keeping
          production history without cluttering active BOM selection.
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Configure realistic work center capacity
          preventing scheduling gridlock. Batch similar work orders on same work center
          minimizing changeover time. Enable work order splitting for large quantities
          improving shop floor flexibility. Monitor work center utilization identifying
          bottlenecks for capacity investment.
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: Run MRP during off-peak hours (overnight)
          preventing performance impact. Configure planning horizon matching realistic
          procurement lead times (3-6 months). Exclude slow-moving products from MPS
          using manual procurement. Optimize reordering rule parameters minimizing
          unnecessary procurement proposals.
        Manufacturing Job Costing: Use standard costing for high-volume products reducing
          valuation calculations. Implement average costing for materials with stable
          prices. Reserve real-time costing for critical products requiring precise
          cost tracking. Periodically review and update standard costs preventing
          large variances.
        default: Optimize performance by configuring appropriate database indexes,
          limiting automated action frequency, and archiving old records that no longer
          require active processing. Monitor system performance after configuration
          changes to identify bottlenecks. Large-scale deployments may require infrastructure
          scaling.
      reporting_configuration:
        Manufacturing Bom: Generate BOM comparison reports showing component changes
          between versions. Create BOM cost analysis reports displaying cost contribution
          by component. Configure BOM where-used reports identifying which products
          use specific components. Enable BOM explosion reports for procurement planning.
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: 'Monitor work center efficiency: actual
          time vs. standard time. Track work center utilization percentage identifying
          underutilized equipment. Generate operation cost variance reports comparing
          estimated vs. actual costs. Create work order completion rate dashboards
          measuring shop floor productivity.'
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: Configure MPS exception reports
          highlighting stockout risks, excess inventory, or capacity violations. Create
          procurement proposal reports for buyer review. Generate forecast accuracy
          reports comparing planned vs. actual demand. Monitor safety stock adequacy
          based on demand variability.
        Manufacturing Job Costing: Generate manufacturing cost variance reports by
          product, order, or time period. Create labor efficiency reports comparing
          actual vs. standard hours. Configure material usage variance reports identifying
          consumption overruns. Monitor manufacturing overhead absorption rate ensuring
          accurate cost allocation.
        default: Data appears in standard Odoo reports and can be included in custom
          report definitions. Configure reporting parameters to control which records
          appear in reports, how data aggregates, and what filters users can apply.
          Export capabilities allow this feature data extraction for external analysis.
      common_mistakes:
        Manufacturing Bom: Failing to version BOMs before changes causes inability
          to reproduce historical production orders. Not testing BOM changes in development
          before production deployment creates shop floor chaos when component requirements
          don't match reality. Forgetting to update component lead times in BOM creates
          procurement delays.
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Setting unrealistic operation times creates
          impossible production schedules shop floor cannot achieve. Forgetting setup
          time separate from per-unit time understates total duration for small batches.
          Not configuring parallel operations misses opportunities to reduce lead
          time through concurrent processing.
        Manufacturing Phantom Bom: Accidentally treating regular assemblies as phantoms
          causes inventory tracking errors. Not documenting phantom assemblies on
          shop floor instructions creates operator confusion. Using phantom BOMs when
          intermediate inventory tracking required loses visibility into assembly-level
          stock.
        Manufacturing Capacity Planning: Ignoring time efficiency factors (breaks,
          changeovers, downtime) creates optimistic schedules. Not accounting for
          shared resources (operators working multiple machines) causes capacity overestimation.
          Forgetting planned maintenance downtime creates last-minute scheduling disruptions.
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: Setting safety stock too high creates
          excess inventory carrying costs. Setting too low causes frequent stockouts.
          Not adjusting forecast based on seasonality creates either shortages or
          overstock. Running MRP too frequently creates planning nervousness—unnecessary
          order rescheduling.
        Manufacturing Job Costing: Mixing costing methods (standard vs. actual) across
          related products creates incomparable profitability analysis. Not updating
          standard costs periodically causes massive variances when actual costs drift.
          Forgetting to account for by-product credits overstates main product costs.
        default: Common configuration errors include enabling features without prerequisite
          modules, configuring in wrong order (company settings before user permissions),
          skipping testing phase with non-production data, and failing to document
          configuration decisions for future reference. These mistakes create issues
          that are difficult to diagnose and require time-consuming rollback procedures.
      validation_checklist:
        Manufacturing Bom: Create manufacturing order for complex product (10+ components),
          verify component reservation accurate, confirm BOM explosion shows all nested
          sub-assemblies, check component availability calculation includes safety
          stock, validate cost rollup matches manual calculation, test BOM with multiple
          variants selecting correct components per variant
        Manufacturing Routing Operations: Schedule manufacturing order with multi-operation
          routing, verify work orders generate for each operation, check operation
          sequence matches routing definition, validate work center capacity consumption,
          confirm operation completion triggers next operation, test parallel operations
          executing simultaneously, verify actual vs. standard time tracking
        Manufacturing Phantom Bom: Create manufacturing order for product with phantom
          sub-assembly, verify MRP explodes through phantom level to leaf components,
          confirm no inventory moves for phantom intermediate, check shop floor documentation
          shows phantom assembly structure for operator guidance, validate costing
          includes all phantom components
        Manufacturing Capacity Planning: Schedule multiple overlapping manufacturing
          orders on same work center, verify capacity constraint prevents overloading,
          check scheduler reschedules operations to available periods, confirm capacity
          alerts when approaching limits, validate finite vs. infinite capacity planning
          behavior, test manual schedule adjustment capability
        Manufacturing Master Production Schedule: Enter demand forecast for multiple
          periods, run MRP and review procurement proposals, verify proposals account
          for current inventory and in-transit supply, check lead time calculations
          matching vendor and manufacturing lead times, confirm safety stock targets
          maintained, test forecast revision triggering proposal updates
        Manufacturing Job Costing: Complete manufacturing order tracking actual component
          usage and operation times, compare actual cost against standard cost, verify
          cost variance posting to accounting, check work center cost allocation,
          confirm by-product value credits main product, validate finished goods inventory
          valuation update
        default: 'Before deploying configuration to production: (1) Test with sample
          data in development environment, (2) Verify user permissions grant appropriate
          access, (3) Confirm integration with related modules works correctly, (4)
          Document configuration decisions and expected behavior, (5) Create database
          backup, (6) Train users on new functionality, (7) Monitor system behavior
          for first week after deployment.'
